### Helper functions to uppercase the column

uppercased<-function(df, col_name) {
  
  df[[col_name]] <- toupper(df[[col_name]])
  df[[col_name]]<-as.factor(df[[col_name]])
  df
}

read_processed_csv<-function(file_path) {
  
  df<-read.csv(file_path, encoding = "UTF-8",quote="`", sep = ";", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)  
  df$X<-NULL 
  df$"Unnamed..0"<-NULL
  df
} 

### Helper function to import the Python generated data

read_processed_csv<-function(file_path) {
  
  df<-read.csv(file_path, encoding = "UTF-8",quote="`", sep = ";", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)  
  df$X<-NULL 
  df$"Unnamed..0"<-NULL
  df
}

# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14563531/combine-column-to-remove-nas
stores_coords_fix<-left_join(stores, stores_coords_to_fill, "store_id") %>%
                 mutate(latitude = coalesce(latitude.x,latitude.y)) %>% 
                 mutate(longitude = coalesce(longitude.x,longitude.y)) %>% 
                 select(-c(latitude.x, latitude.y, longitude.x, longitude.y))

stores_coords_fix_known<-stores_coords_fix %>%
  filter(!is.na(latitude)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(longitude))

stores_coords_still_missing<-anti_join(stores,stores_coords_fix_known,by="store_id")

write.csv(stores_coords_still_missing,file.path(export_dir,"stores_coords_still_missing.csv"))

Within the county there are four administrative subdivisions:

#### As observed above, the second townships may closely correspond with more rural areas.

allegheny_cities<-allegheny_shape %>% filter(CLASS_OF_M=="CITY")
